'''Jerome D. Mack''' (a.k.a. '''Jerry Mack''') (1920-1998) was an American banker, real estate investor, political fundraiser and philanthropist in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]. He was the founder and President of the Bank of Las Vegas and, later, the Valley Bank. He was the President of the [[Riviera (hotel and casino)|Riviera]] casino as well as Director of the [[Four Queens]] and [[Dunes (hotel and casino)|Dunes]] casinos. He was a major fundraiser for the [[Nevada Democratic Party]] and active in Jewish philanthropy both in Las Vegas and [[Israel]]. He was one of the founders of the [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]] (UNLV).

==Biography==
===Early life===
Jerome D. Mack was born on November 6, 1920 in [[Albion, Michigan]].<ref name="lasvegassun">[http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/1998/sep/28/lv-civic-leader-mack-dies/ LV civic leader Mack dies], ''[[Las Vegas Sun]]'', September 28, 1998</ref> His father, Nate Mack, was a haberdasher.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> His mother was Jenny (Solomon) Mack.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> He moved to [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] with his parents in 1929, when he was nine years old.<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ">[http://www.unlv.edu/business/nbhof/jerome-mack University of Nevada, Las Vegas: Jerome D. Mack]</ref> 

He attended the Boulder City Grammar School and graduated from the [[Las Vegas High School]] in 1938.<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ"/> He then graduated from the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA), where he was a member of the [[Zeta Beta Tau]] [[fraternity]].<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ"/> He served as a navigator in the Army Air Corps during [[World War II]].<ref name="lasvegassun"/>

===Career===
He established the Bank of Las Vegas in 1954.<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ"/> Fifteen years later, in 1969, it merged with the Valley Bank of Reno, a band established by [[E. Parry Thomas]], and became known as Valley Bank.<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ"/> It was later acquired by [[Bank of America]].<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ"/>

He served as Vice President of the Continental Connector Corporation, Vice Chairman of the United Tanker Group, and President of First Bancorporation (later known as the Nevada National Bank, which went on to merge with [[Wells Fargo]]).<ref name="lasvegassun"/> He also served on the Board of Directors of the Pioneer Title and Insurance Corporation.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> He served on the Board of Directors of the [[Las Vegas Chamber of Commerce]] for two terms.<ref name="lasvegassun"/>

He was the President of the [[Riviera (hotel and casino)|Riviera]] casino as well as Director of the [[Four Queens]] and the [[Dunes (hotel and casino)|Dunes]] hotel-casinos.<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ"/> He started developing the [[McCarran Center]] in 1991.<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ"/> Located South of the [[McCarran International Airport]] and spanning 100 acres of land, it includes offices, a hotel and several restaurants.<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ"/>

===Politics===
He served as Finance Chair of the [[Nevada Democratic Party]] in the 1960s.<ref name="latimeskaren">Karen Mack, [http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-mag-april052009-mylasvegas-story.html The Big Secret], ''The Los Angeles Times'', April 5, 2009</ref> He then served on the Democratic National Finance Council and the Democratic Party National Committee.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> From 1958 to 1980, he was state coordinator and treasurer for [[Howard Cannon]], a Democratic member of the [[United States Senate]].<ref name="lasvegassun"/> In 1964, he served as the Nevada Finance Chairman for [[Lyndon Johnson]]'s bid for President.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> Four years later, in 1968, he was state coordinator for [[Hubert Humphrey]]'s presidential campaign.<ref name="lasvegassun"/>

In 1972, he was appointed to the Nevada Tax Commission by Governor [[Mike O'Callaghan]].<ref name="lasvegassun"/> By 1975, he became its Chairman.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> Later in the 1970s, President [[Jimmy Carter]] appointed him as a member of the nominating commission for U.S. Circuit Judges for the 9th Circuit Court.<ref name="lasvegassun"/>

With E. Parry Thomas, he lobbied state legislator [[Bill Harrah]] as well as former Governors [[Grant Sawyer]] and [[Paul Laxalt]] to pass a law legalizing the corporate ownership of casinos.<ref name="latimeskaren"/> According to Mack's daughter Karen, this put an end to corruption in Las Vegas, as it enforced more regulations and disclosures for the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]].<ref name="latimeskaren"/>

===Philanthropy===
In the 1950s, he helped found the Nevada Southern College with [[Maude Frazer]] and [[Archie Grant]].<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ"/> It later became known as the [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]].<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ"/> He also served on a committee to select the first Board of Trustees of UNLV.<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ"/> In 1967, with his business partner, E. Parry Thomas, he donated 400 additional acres of land to expand the campus.<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ"/> The two men also funded the construction of the basketball stadium at UNLV, which was named the '''Thomas & Mack Center''' in their honor.<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ"/> Later, the '''Thomas & Mack Legal Clinic''' as well as the '''Thomas & Mack Moot Court Building''' were also named after them.<ref name="unlvfoundation">[http://www.unlv.edu/news-story/conversation-joyce-mack UNLV Foundation: A Conversation with Joyce Mack], May 13, 2013</ref> Mack chaired a fundraising effort for the construction of the Artemus Ham Hall on the UNLV campus.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> He was inducted into the Business Hall of Fame of the Lee Business School at UNLV.<ref name="univ"/> Additionally, he served on a committee to establish the first Board of Trustees at his alma mater, UCLA.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> He was also a founding member of the UCLA Chancellors Association.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> 

He served on the Boulder Dam Council of the [[Boy Scouts of America]]. Additionally, he was the Founder and Director of the [[Boys Club of Nevada]] and served as Chairman for advance gifts of  the [[United Way of America|United Way]].<ref name="lasvegassun"/> He was the 1972 recipient of the United Way Leadership Award as well as the National Conference of Christians and Jews Silver Medallion Award.<ref name="lasvegassun"/>

He served as President of [[Temple Beth Sholom (Las Vegas, Nevada)|Temple Beth Sholom]], a synagogue in Las Vegas.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> Later, he established the Nate Mack School at the temple, in honor of his father.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> He was also President of B'nai B'rith.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> He served on the Board of Trustees of the [[American Jewish Committee]] and the National Committee of the [[United Jewish Appeal]].<ref name="lasvegassun"/> He funded the Chair in Cancer Research at the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]].<ref name="lasvegassun"/> From 1959 to 1976, he served as Chairman of the [[State of Israel Bonds|Israel Bonds]] Campaigns, a fundraising effort to develop the state of Israel.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> In 1973, he was a recipient of the Prime Minister's Medal of Israel.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> That same year, he also received the Silver Anniversary Award from the State of Israel.<ref name="lasvegassun"/>

===Personal life===
He married Joyce (Rosenberg) Mack in 1946.<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="unlvfoundation"/> They had met at UCLA.<ref name="lasvegassun"/><ref name="univ"/> They had three daughters
*Barbara Mack Feller Levine.<ref name="unlvfoundation"/> She married Norman Levine.<ref name="lasvegassun"/>
*[[Karen Mack]].<ref name="unlvfoundation"/> She married [[Russell Goldsmith]], the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of [[City National Bank]].<ref name="lasvegassun"/>
*Marilynn Mack.<ref name="unlvfoundation"/>

===Death===
He died of cancer on September 26, 1998 in Los Angeles, California.<ref name="lasvegassun"/> His funeral took place at Temple Emanuel in [[Beverly Hills, California]].<ref name="lasvegassun"/>

